e ingress with a class first, then removes it to establish the broken state. Let me trace through the precondition steps to see if there's a final modification that strips the class. So the precondition is actually setting up the broken state where the ingress has no class, and `demo-ingress.yaml` in its current form is also broken. But when I look at the actual resource file, it shows `ingressClassName: ingress-2`, which suggests that's the corrected version. Let me check what the current ingress in the cluster actually looks like to understand the discrepancy. demo-app` ingress has `demo.example.com` as the host, which suggests it was created from a different manifest than `demo-ingress.yaml`. If both `demo-app.yaml` and `demo-ingress.yaml` tried to create an ingress named `demo-app`, the later one would overwrite the first, but the current state shows the `demo.example.com` version is still there. I need to check whether `demo-app.yaml` actually exists in the class_only_upgrade resources or if something else is going on.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3068,"cache_read_input_tokens":38273,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3068},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"351c83fc-b52a-4712-8f46-2e9809c42328","uuid":"7133af79-050b-4b4f-a716-a4ce5c7d51d3","request_id":"req_011CcQVK669QrgubaxkEt9es"}
