sk specifies two controllers should be running) and then create the necessary services and Ingress resources.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the task description says the demo Ingress \"currently has no ingress class,\" but there's no demo Ingress for `class.example.com` in the cluster yet—the `demo-ingress.yaml` file would be what sets up that broken state initially. But that file already has `ingressClassName: ingress-2`, so I need to figure out what's actually happening here. I'm getting caught in circles trying to figure out whether the file I'm looking at is the broken or fixed state. Let me step back and focus on what actually matters: what does the test need to pass? I need to create an `ingress-gateway.demo.svc.cluster.local` service and work from there to understand what the ingress configuration should be.\n\nLooking at the current state, the `demo-app` deployment and service are already set up correctly, but there's no ingress-gateway service and no ingress rule for `class.example.com`. The ingress-nginx controller is running with specific class configurations. Since the task mentions both ingress-1 and ingress-2, I'll start by deploying the necessary ingress components to make the test pass. I'm realizing the task wants me to create or update a demo Ingress specifically for `class.example.com`, not modify the existing `demo-app` ingress which handles a different host. The `demo-app` ingress is for a separate test case, so I need to create a new Ingress resource that routes `class.example.com` to the appropriate backend using the second ingress controller.\n\nBefore deploying a separate ingress-nginx controller, I should check whether the existing controller can watch multiple ingress classes or if I need to set up a second controller instance. Let me examine the controller configuration more closely to understand what's needed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens